The key to this problem is to use the identity $\tan(\pi - x) = -\tan(x)$.

Apply this identity to the elements in the matrix:

First row:
\[ \tan^2 \frac{\pi}{7}, \tan^2 \frac{2\pi}{7}, \tan^2 \frac{3\pi}{7} \]

Second row:
\[ \tan^2 \frac{4\pi}{7} = \tan^2 \left(\pi - \frac{3\pi}{7}\right) = \tan^2 \frac{3\pi}{7} \]
\[ \tan^2 \frac{5\pi}{7} = \tan^2 \left(\pi - \frac{2\pi}{7}\right) = \tan^2 \frac{2\pi}{7} \]
\[ \tan^2 \frac{6\pi}{7} = \tan^2 \left(\pi - \frac{\pi}{7}\right) = \tan^2 \frac{\pi}{7} \]

Third row:
\[ \tan^2 \frac{7\pi}{7} = \tan^2 \pi = 0 \]
\[ \tan^2 \frac{8\pi}{7} = \tan^2 \left(\pi + \frac{\pi}{7}\right) = \tan^2 \frac{\pi}{7} \]
\[ \tan^2 \frac{9\pi}{7} = \tan^2 \left(\pi + \frac{2\pi}{7}\right) = \tan^2 \frac{2\pi}{7} \]

So, the matrix becomes:
\[
\begin{vmatrix}
\tan^2 \frac{\pi}{7} & \tan^2 \frac{2\pi}{7} & \tan^2 \frac{3\pi}{7} \\
\tan^2 \frac{3\pi}{7} & \tan^2 \frac{2\pi}{7} & \tan^2 \frac{\pi}{7} \\
0 & \tan^2 \frac{\pi}{7} & \tan^2 \frac{2\pi}{7}
\end{vmatrix}
\]

Now, expand the determinant along the first column:
\begin{align*}
\tan^2 \frac{\pi}{7} \cdot
\begin{vmatrix}
\tan^2 \frac{2\pi}{7} & \tan^2 \frac{\pi}{7} \\
\tan^2 \frac{\pi}{7} & \tan^2 \frac{2\pi}{7}
\end{vmatrix}
- \tan^2 \frac{3\pi}{7} \cdot
\begin{vmatrix}
\tan^2 \frac{2\pi}{7} & \tan^2 \frac{3\pi}{7} \\
\tan^2 \frac{\pi}{7} & \tan^2 \frac{2\pi}{7}
\end{vmatrix}
+ 0 \cdot
\begin{vmatrix}
\tan^2 \frac{2\pi}{7} & \tan^2 \frac{3\pi}{7} \\
\tan^2 \frac{2\pi}{7} & \tan^2 \frac{\pi}{7}
\end{vmatrix}
\end{align*}

Simplifying the determinants:
\begin{align*}
\tan^2 \frac{\pi}{7} \cdot
\left(\tan^4 \frac{2\pi}{7} - \tan^4 \frac{\pi}{7}\right)
- \tan^2 \frac{3\pi}{7} \cdot
\left(\tan^4 \frac{2\pi}{7} - \tan^2 \frac{2\pi}{7} \tan^2 \frac{3\pi}{7}\right)
\end{align*}

Since the matrix has two identical rows, the determinant is zero:
\[ \boxed{0} \]
